<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic situation at Sculptor Capital Manage=
ment Inc. is this.=C2=A0In July, Sculptor, a publicly traded asset manageme=
nt firm,=C2=A0signed a deal to sell itself to Rithm Capital Corp. for $11.1=
5 per share. Then, in August, a group of hedge fund managers led by Boaz We=
instein and including Bill Ackman, Marc Lasry and Jeff Yass <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33068739.259426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDgtMjEvZXZlcnlvbmUtd2FudHMt=
YS1waWVjZS1vZi1zY3VscHRvcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDE4MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXV=
tPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEwMTgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaW=
duPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7a17ec3d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  offered to b=
uy Sculptor</a> for $12.25 per share instead.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sculptor=E2=80=99s board rejected Weinstein=E2=
=80=99s offer, worrying that it was too conditional. Weinstein didn=E2=80=
=99t have fully committed financing, and his deal (like Rithm=E2=80=99s) re=
quired the consent of Sculptor=E2=80=99s investor clients: Weinstein=E2=80=
=99s proposed deal would allow him to walk away if fewer than 50.1% of Scul=
ptor=E2=80=99s hedge fund clients, or fewer than 80% of its real estate and=
 collateralized loan obligation clients, consented to him taking over. (Rit=
hm=E2=80=99s deal required 85% consents.)=C2=A0Rithm planned to keep Sculpt=
or=E2=80=99s current chief executive officer and chief investment officer, =
Jimmy Levin, whom Sculptor=E2=80=99s clients presumably like. Weinstein wou=
ld presumably put himself in charge of Sculptor, and the board worried that=
 this would scare clients away, the deal would not get the required consent=
s, and Weinstein would walk away, leaving Sculptor with nothing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sculptor=E2=80=99s board said this =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the $12.25 Weinstein deal was too risky, so it would stick with the $=
11.15 Rithm deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0and Weinstein=E2=80=99s consortium responde=
d, over the last few months, by (1) firming up their financing, so that now=
 they have a bid backed by fully committed financing, (2) <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33068739.259426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTAtMDMvdGhlLXNlYy1oYWQtYS1idX=
N5LXdlZWs_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAxODIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc=
291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMDE4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1be00105" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  removing most of the client-c=
onsent conditions</a>, so that now they have a bid that is not contingent o=
n hedge fund client consents at all<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foo=
tnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none =
!important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block=
;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> and (3) raising their bid to $12.76, with a possibility of $13 if Scul=
ptor engaged with them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The result was:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Weinstein=E2=80=99s bid ($12.76 or so)=
 was=C2=A0higher<em>=C2=A0</em>than the Rithm deal ($11.15).</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Weinstein=E2=80=99s bid was much less risky than=
 Sculptor originally argued. The financing is locked up, and the client-con=
sent risk is lower: Even if all of Sculptor=E2=80=99s hedge fund clients sa=
y no to Weinstein, the deal will still close and Sculptor=E2=80=99s shareho=
lders will still get their $12.76.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>
<em>Rithm=E2=80=99s=C2=A0</em>deal was now <em>riskier</em>: Rithm should h=
ave no problem getting financing or client consents (indeed, it seems to ha=
ve already gotten the 85% consents it needs), but its deal (like any deal) =
is contingent on a vote of Sculptor=E2=80=99s shareholders. And the shareho=
lders would prefer to get $12.76 rather than $11.15. Sculptor=E2=80=99s sto=
ck has traded above $11.15 since Weinstein=E2=80=99s bid became public; it =
has been above $12 since Oct. 2. Sculptor=E2=80=99s shareholders do not wan=
t the $11.15 Rithm deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0they think the stock is worth more t=
han that =E2=80=94=C2=A0and so they are unlikely to vote for it. They could=
 vote down the Rithm deal and hope that Weinstein will still be there, at $=
13 or $12.76 or <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33=
068739.259426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwM=
jMtMTAtMTEvc2N1bHB0b3Itc29mdGVucy1hLWJpdC1vbi13ZWluc3RlaW4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAx=
ODIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXR=
tX3Rlcm09MjMxMDE4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
9cd0863c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">  even $12.25</a>. The stock price suggests they would do=
 that.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sculptor really does not want to sell to Weins=
tein, though, so last week it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/33068739.259426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2F=
ydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTAtMTIvZnR4LWhhZC1tYW55LWJhZC1zcHJlYWRzaGVldHM_Y21waWQ9Qk=
JEMTAxODIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0Z=
XImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMDE4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBc03d5307" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">  cut a new deal with Rithm</a>. The new deal=C2=A0=
raised the price to $12.00 per share, still below Weinstein=E2=80=99s offer=
. In return, Sculptor =E2=80=A6=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>get rid=C2=A0<=
/em>of the shareholder vote (you can=E2=80=99t do that), but it did a lot t=
o lock up the shareholder vote:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Roughly <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/33068739.259426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNo=
aXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE0MDM2MTIzMDQ3OTY4L255MjAwMDk5Mzl4MTJ=
fZGVmbTE0YS5odG0jdFNPQw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8b7b9cd5" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> 26%</a>=
 of the voting shares are owned by Jimmy Levin and other current Sculptor e=
xecutives, who have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/33068739.259426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0M=
DMyNTYvMDAwMTE0MDM2MTIzMDQ3OTY4L255MjAwMDk5Mzl4MTJfZGVmbTE0YS5odG0jdFZB/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2cdcb5ce" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> signed voting agreements</a> commi=
tting them to support the Rithm deal. (Another 15.8% of the vote is owned b=
y Dan Och, Sculptor=E2=80=99s estranged founder, and Robert Shafir, another=
 former Sculptor CEO, both of whom have come out against the Rithm deal and=
 would presumably vote no.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A few =
years ago, Sculptor sold some warrants on its stock to Delaware Life Insura=
nce Co. As part of the new merger deal, Rithm <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/33068739.259426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmN=
oaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE0MDM2MTIzMDQ4MjE1L2VmMjAwMTI1ODhfc2=
MxM2QuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4bfb68c8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> bought those warrant=
s</a>, giving it another roughly 6.5% of the voting stock. (The price it pa=
id for those warrants comes to roughly $6.35 per warrant, and they have an =
exercise price of $7.95 per share, meaning that Rithm is paying roughly $14=
.30 per share for these extra votes =E2=80=94=C2=A0versus the $12 per share=
 it is offering to public shareholders.) So between the warrants and the vo=
ting agreements, Rithm has about one-third of the shares committed to vote =
in favor of the deal: not the majority it needs, but closer.</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The original Rithm deal required not only a vote=
 of all shareholders, but a second vote of all=C2=A0<em>outside=C2=A0</em>s=
hareholders, excluding Levin and other current executives (and Och and othe=
r estranged former executives). The voting agreements would not have helped=
 there. And the outside shareholders, the=C2=A0ones who have been buying an=
d selling the stock at above $12, presumably want more money and would be h=
ard to persuade to vote for Rithm. The new deal just gets rid of that secon=
d vote: Now the deal can close without the approval of a majority of=C2=A0o=
utside shareholders.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The new deal =
also raises Rithm=E2=80=99s breakup fee: Now, if Sculptor does end up selli=
ng to someone else, Rithm gets $20.3 million, instead of the previous $16.6=
 million breakup fee.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This was, I think, a pretty odd move: Sculptor=
=E2=80=99s board was so opposed to taking the Weinstein deal that it took a=
 lower deal from Rithm, and made it harder for its shareholders to reject t=
hat deal. There are two possible explanations:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Sculptor=E2=80=99s board is=C2=A0so<em=
>=C2=A0</em>worried that a deal with Weinstein would tank the company, and =
that the company tanking would give Weinstein an excuse to get out of the d=
eal, that it had to stick with Rithm=C2=A0<em>and take the choice out of sh=
areholders=E2=80=99 hands</em>. The risk was too great that shareholders wo=
uld be seduced by Weinstein=E2=80=99s higher number and would vote down the=
 Rithm deal, and then the company would collapse and shareholders would get=
 nothing. The board is protecting shareholders from themselves, by giving t=
hem a deal they don=E2=80=99t want but that is nonetheless best for them.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Sculptor=E2=80=99s board is friendl=
y with Jimmy Levin, they=E2=80=99ve paid him a lot, they want him to keep h=
is job, and so they are fighting to keep a deal that is best for him even t=
hough it is worse for shareholders.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The first explanation was, I think, plausible =
at the beginning, but it has become less plausible each time Weinstein has =
removed a condition from his bid. =E2=80=9CThere is no way that Boaz Weinst=
ein will get 50% of Sculptor=E2=80=99s hedge fund clients to work with him =
instead of Jimmy Levin=E2=80=9D makes some sense, but his deal is no longer=
 contingent on=C2=A0<em>any=C2=A0</em>of the hedge fund clients agreeing to=
 stick with him. (It remains contingent on the real estate and CLO clients =
consenting, though, as well as presumably on some amount of general =E2=80=
=9CJimmy Levin doesn=E2=80=99t sabotage the business on his way out the doo=
r=E2=80=9D conditions.) Sculptor has continued making the same complaints a=
bout Weinstein=E2=80=99s bid, even as the bid itself has changed=C2=A0in an=
swer to those complaints.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In fact, when Sculptor=C2=A0<em>started=C2=A0<=
/em>the process of selling itself, Sculptor=E2=80=99s own board announced=
=C2=A0that it would sell itself to the highest bidder, subject to an 80% cl=
ient consent threshold and without any requirement that the bidder retain a=
ny of the current staff.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important;=
 background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> It understood that, as a matter of fiduciary duties to shareholders, i=
t couldn=E2=80=99t try to preserve Levin=E2=80=99s job, and it understood t=
hat, as a matter of how asset-management deals are done, the buyer would ex=
pect to get client consents. Now that Weinstein wants to buy Sculptor at th=
e highest price, subject to a lower client consent threshold and without=C2=
=A0retaining Jimmy Levin, Sculptor says =E2=80=9Cno obviously that=E2=80=99=
s impossible.=E2=80=9D But that=E2=80=99s what Sculptor itself proposed!</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All of this does=C2=A0<em>kind=C2=A0of </em>su=
ggest that there might be something to the second explanation?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway, Sculptor has <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33068739.259426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9=
BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE0MDM2MTIzMDQ3OTY4L255MjAwMDk5Mz=
l4MTJfZGVmbTE0YS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB97340ac5" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">scheduled =
its shareholder meeting</a> for Nov. 16, hoping to get a majority and close=
 the Rithm deal soon afterward. Weinstein has a standstill agreement that p=
revents him from making a public bid or tender offer, but it expires in Dec=
ember, so Sculptor is trying=C2=A0to get the Rithm deal done before then.=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The traditional next step here is for the jilt=
ed party =E2=80=94=C2=A0Weinstein =E2=80=94=C2=A0to go to Delaware Chancery=
 Court, lay out all of this stuff, say =E2=80=9Cthis is not what the board =
is supposed to do,=E2=80=9D and try to get the court to block the Rithm dea=
l. Weinstein has not done that, for whatever reason (possibly the standstil=
l?).=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But somebody has! It is tough for Sculptor tha=
t they have an estranged founder who <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/33068739.259426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdz=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTAtMTcvZGFuLW9jaC1zdWVzLXNjdWxwdG9yLXJpdGhtLW92ZXItdGV=
ybXMtb2YtcHJvcG9zZWQtYWNxdWlzaXRpb24_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAxODIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdX=
RtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMDE4JnV0b=
V9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB189ea880" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  ta=
kes a keen interest in all of this</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Dan Och and a group of former executives of Sc=
ulptor Capital Management Inc. sued the hedge fund and proposed acquirer Ri=
thm Capital Corp., saying the $676 million deal would shortchange investors=
 in favor of protecting Sculptor Chief Executive Officer Jimmy Levin=E2=80=
=99s job.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Och, who left New York-based Sculptor in 2019,=
 said Tuesday in a statement that he wants a Delaware judge to halt the buy=
out until a rival group led by Saba Capital Management=E2=80=99s Boaz Weins=
tein is able to present its higher bid to shareholders. Weinstein=E2=80=99s=
 group, which includes billionaires Jeff Yass, Marc Lasry and Bill Ackman, =
has offered to pay $13 a share for Sculptor, which last week accepted Rithm=
=E2=80=99s $12 bid.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sculptor directors backing Levin have made it =
clear that =E2=80=9Cthey favor only one result =E2=80=94 the preservation o=
f management=E2=80=99s jobs and compensation, at the expense of shareholder=
 value,=E2=80=9D Och said. The suit was filed in Delaware Chancery Court.</=
p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/33068739.259426/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVu=
dHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3J5bTFCWnY5Q01DNC92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B6f499e44" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> Och=E2=80=99s complaint</a>, which makes these and othe=
r points. On the client consents<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footno=
te-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !im=
portant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When it came to Rithm, the Special Committee a=
ccepted a client-consent condition that would allow Rithm to walk away if m=
erely 15% of the clients=C2=A0of Sculptor=E2=80=99s hedge fund objected to =
the deal. Yet when it came to the Consortium, the Special Committee effecti=
vely required the Consortium to be bound to purchase the Company even in th=
e extraordinary scenario that all employees and clients fled the Company, l=
eaving it an empty shell. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Incredibly, while maintaining that the client-=
consent condition in the Consortium=E2=80=99s proposal imposed unacceptable=
 deal risk, the Special Committee refused to conduct reasonable due diligen=
ce to determine whether a significant number of clients would, in fact, opp=
ose the Consortium=E2=80=99s offer. Initially, the Special Committee relied=
 solely upon the opinion of Sculptor management that clients would not cons=
ent to a deal that did not preserve their role.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When pressed publicly, the Special Committee r=
etained a consultant to evaluate the views of the Company=E2=80=99s clients=
, but the Special Committee refused to allow the consultant to speak with t=
he clients (even though the clients are obviously aware of the publicly ann=
ounced sale process).</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the vote:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is little doubt the Merger would have fa=
iled the Disinterested Vote. Sculptor=E2=80=99s stock is now trading above =
the deal price (closing at $12.27 on October 16, 2023), demonstrating that =
public stockholders still believe that the Company is worth more than what =
Rithm is offering and should be able to obtain it. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is apparent that the Company and Rithm waiv=
ed the standstill, eliminated the Disinterested Vote, and increased the bre=
ak-up fee for the sole purpose of pushing through the Merger against the in=
terests of the stockholders as a whole. An unconflicted Board of Directors =
would never have agreed to such measures.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/33068739.259426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9l=
ZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE0MDM2MTIzMDQ4NTgzL255MjAwMTEyNzU4eDFfZGVmYTE=
0YS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7e1efb32" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Sculptor=E2=80=99s sta=
tement</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Special Committee=E2=80=99s ro=
le is to recommend the transaction that it believes is in the best interest=
 of stockholders, based on price and certainty of closing.=C2=A0Contrary to=
 Dan Och=E2=80=99s assertions in the baseless lawsuit filed today that he t=
oo seeks to act in the best interest of stockholders, his ongoing campaign =
against the company, including his conduct throughout the Special Committee=
=E2=80=99s process, has cost stockholders significant value.=C2=A0His compl=
aint is replete with materially misleading statements, and Sculptor intends=
 to vigorously defend itself.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose we will see in court. There=E2=80=99=
s a hearing for Nov. 9 or 10, about a week before the vote on the Rithm dea=
l, and a judge either will or won=E2=80=99t let that vote go forward.=C2=A0=
</p>
