er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">Sharing Names and Sharing Information: Incide=
ntal Similarities between CEOS and Analysts Can Lead to Favoritism in Infor=
mation Disclosure</a>,=E2=80=9D by Omri Even-Tov, Kanyuan Huang, Brett True=
man, Jon Bogard and Noah Goldstein. One meta-analysis in empirical finance =
that I would like to read is, like:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">What sorts of empirical finance quest=
ions are of interest to both quantitative investors and finance academics? =
(Obviously lots of them.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">What sor=
ts of questions are only of interest to investors and are not addressed in =
the academic literature? (Presumably some of my readers know these, but won=
=E2=80=99t tell me.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">What sorts of=
 questions are only of interest to academics and not investors?</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you work at a hedge fund and your model ove=
rweights sell-side price targets from analysts whose names are similar to t=
he names of the CEOs they cover, I would very much like to hear from you. I=
 mean, if you=E2=80=99ve been tracking this for years, but also if you read=
 this paper last month (or today!) and immediately started implementing it =
in your model. Is this the sort of paper that you read and think =E2=80=9Co=
oh there=E2=80=99s alpha here,=E2=80=9D or is it just the sort of paper tha=
t you read and think =E2=80=9Cha, that=E2=80=99s funny, that should be in M=
oney Stuff=E2=80=9D?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously if you work at a hedge fund and you =
skip all the modeling and just=C2=A0<em>hire analysts with the same names a=
s CEOs to get inside information=C2=A0</em>then I really want to hear from =
you.</p>
